# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: denotational-domains
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] In mathematics, the **Bourbaki–Witt theorem** in order theory, named after Nicolas Bourbaki and Ernst Witt, is a basic fixed-point theorem for partially ordered sets.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Such a function *f* is called *inflationary* or *progressive*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] If the poset *X* is finite then the statement of the theorem has a clear interpretation that leads to the proof.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] where *x*0 is any element of *X*, is monotone increasing.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] It follows that *x*∞ is a fixed point of *f*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] A maximal element, *if any*, is trivially a fixed point of the inflationary map f .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] In particular, if Zorn's lemma is available (which is equivalent to assuming the axiom of choice), then the theorem holds trivially.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] However, the theorem is typically used in a proof that the axiom of choice implies Zorn's lemma as follows.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] We first prove it for the case where *X* is chain complete and has no maximal element.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] This is allowed as, by assumption, the set is non-empty.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Then *f*(*x*) > *x*, so *f* is an inflationary function with no fixed point, contradicting the theorem.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] This special case of Zorn's lemma is then applied to the set $P'$ of all chains in a given poset P , ordered by set inclusion.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] We get a maximal element in $P'$ ; i.e., a maximal chain in P .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] This proves the Hausdorff maximality principle, that every poset has a maximal chain, which is easily seen to be equivalent to Zorn's lemma (see also Zorn's lemma § Proof from the Hausdorff maximal principle).
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] In the following, to say that an ordinal α is *embeddable in* a set *X* is to say that there exists an injection $f:U(\alpha )\hookrightarrow X$ from the underlying set of α to *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Such an injection amounts to a well-ordering of the image of *f* as a subset of *X*, thereby witnessing that that subset can be well-ordered.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Let β be the Hartogs number for the set *U(X)* of the given poset *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] By definition this is the set of all ordinals embeddable in *U(X)*, itself an ordinal not embeddable in *U(X)* or we would have β ϵ β.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] (Equivalently, β is the least ordinal not embeddable in *U(X)*, necessarily a cardinal.) Let $x_{0}$ witness the non-emptiness of *X*, to serve as the basis for the following recursive construction of a chain in *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] For each ordinal $\alpha \in \beta$ such that $x_{\alpha }$ is defined, define $x_{\alpha +1}=f(x_{\alpha }).$ Since *f* is inflationary, $x_{\alpha }\leq x_{\alpha +1}$ in the poset *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] For each limit ordinal $\lambda \in \beta$ such that $x_{\alpha }$ is defined for all $\alpha <\lambda$ , define $x_{\lambda }=\sup\{x_{\alpha }|\alpha <\lambda \}.$ Then $x_{\alpha }\leq x_{\lambda }$ for all $\alpha <\lambda$ .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The $\sup$ exists by chain-completeness of the poset *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Now if *f* is strictly increasing on all of β, this would constitute an embedding of β, the order type of that chain, in *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] But that's impossible by Hartogs' Lemma.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Hence there must exist $\alpha <\beta$ such that $x_{\alpha +1}=x_{\alpha }$ , bringing the construction of the chain to a halt at $x_{\alpha }$ , the promised fixed point.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The foregoing argument avoids anything that depends on the Axiom of Choice.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Now it is tempting to argue that the Hartogs number for the set *X* must be the least cardinal greater than the cardinality of *X*.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] After all, surely the above recursive construction must eventually exhaust all the elements of *X* long before exhausting all the ordinals.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] However a set that can only embed finite ordinals is called Dedekind-finite and ZF can have models in which infinite Dedekind-finite sets exist.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The Hartogs number for such sets is therefore ω, and posets on them cannot contain any infinite chains.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] To be sure we have not somehow smuggled in anything not provable in ZF without choice, we should stick to what is provable in ZF alone.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Otherwise applications of the Bourbaki–Witt theorem to proofs relating equivalences between variants of the Axiom of Choice, such as done below, may introduce circularities into the reasoning.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The theorem can also be proved by *adapting* a typical proof showing that the axiom of choice implies Zorn’s lemma.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Indeed, let $\operatorname {Well} (X)$ denote the set of all well-ordered subsets of X .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] given by $g(S)=f(\sup S).$ If f has no fixed point, then $g(S)$ is a strict upper bound of S .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] From this, one concludes a contradiction as in a standard proof of Zorn’s lemma.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] For the sake of completeness, here is a sketch of the proof following T.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Let $\operatorname {Well}$ be the class of all well-ordered sets.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Then for each A in $\operatorname {Well}$ , using an iteration of g , we construct a sequence $x_{a}$ of distinct elements in X indexed by A .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] For arbitrary A , we use transfinite recursion or transfinite induction to construct the sequences in a similar way.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] It is not hard to see non-isomorphic A 's produce different sequences; i.e., $\rho$ is injective modulo isomorphisms.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Note the above argument does not rely on the axiom of choice.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] (In the case of a proof of Zorn's lemma, Choice is used to define an inflationary map.) Also, we needed $\sup S$ only for well-ordered subsets S of P .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The argument therefore establishes the following.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Just as Zorn's lemma can be proved without transfinite induction or the theory of well-ordering and ordinals, it is possible to give a proof of the theorem that only uses a basic set theory.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The idea here is first to prove a general lemma below, used implicitly in a traditional proof of Hausdorff's maximal principle and also noted independently by Kneser as well as Guillermo L.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] The Bourbaki–Witt theorem follows since the function $g(C)=f(\sup C)$ has the property stated in the lemma if f has no fixed point.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Following the authors, we say a chain $C\subset P$ is *good* if for each $S\trianglelefteq C$ , we have either $S=C$ or $S^{+}\trianglelefteq C$ .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Let $\Gamma$ be the set of all good chains in P .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] On $\Gamma$ , $\trianglelefteq$ is the same as set inclusion.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] If C is a good chain in P , then $C^{+}$ is a good chain in P .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] For (1), given two good chains $C,D$ , let S be the union of all chains that are both the initial segments of C and $D.$ Clearly, S itself is an initial segment of the two; i.e., it is the largest common initial segment.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] If $S^{+}\trianglelefteq C,D$ , then that would contradict the largest-ness of S .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] By (1), either $C\triangleleft D$ or $D\triangleleft C$ , but the latter is not possible.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] To show it is good, suppose $S\triangleleft U$ .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Indeed, if y is in S , then y is in a good chain D .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] If $D\trianglelefteq C$ , then y is in C .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Otherwise, by (1), $C\trianglelefteq D$ .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] We have $y\leq x$ by $S\triangleleft U$ and so again y is in C .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Hence, $S\subset C$ and that implies $S\triangleleft C$ as S is already an initial segment of U .
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] This finishes the proof of the fact that U is good.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Hence, a good well-ordered set is exactly the same as what Kneser calls *Kette* (and so the above proof reduces to Kneser's proof).
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] Besides a proof of Zorn's lemma, Bourbaki–Witt has some other applications.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] In particular in computer science, it is used in the theory of computable functions.
[src:denotational-domains/bourbaki-witt-theorem] It is also used to define recursive data types, e.g. linked lists, in domain theory.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The primary motivation for the study of domains, which was initiated by Dana Scott in the late 1960s, was the search for a denotational semantics of the lambda calculus.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In this formalism, one considers "functions" specified by certain terms in the language.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In a purely syntactic way, one can go from simple functions to functions that take other functions as their input arguments.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Using again just the syntactic transformations available in this formalism, one can obtain so-called fixed-point combinators (the best-known of which is the Y combinator); these, by definition, have the property that *f*(**Y**(*f*)) = **Y**(*f*) for all functions *f*.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] To formulate such a denotational semantics, one might first try to construct a *model* for the lambda calculus, in which a genuine (total) function is associated with each lambda term.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Such a model would formalize a link between the lambda calculus as a purely syntactic system and the lambda calculus as a notational system for manipulating concrete mathematical functions.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The combinator calculus is such a model.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] However, the elements of the combinator calculus are functions from functions to functions; in order for the elements of a model of the lambda calculus to be of arbitrary domain and range, they could not be true functions, only partial functions.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Scott got around this difficulty by formalizing a notion of "partial" or "incomplete" information to represent computations that have not yet returned a result.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] This was modeled by considering, for each domain of computation (e.g. the natural numbers), an additional element that represents an *undefined* output, i.e. the "result" of a computation that never ends.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In addition, the domain of computation is equipped with an *ordering relation*, in which the "undefined result" is the least element.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The important step to finding a model for the lambda calculus is to consider only those functions (on such a partially ordered set) that are guaranteed to have least fixed points.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The set of these functions, together with an appropriate ordering, is again a "domain" in the sense of the theory.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] But the restriction to a subset of all available functions has another great benefit: it is possible to obtain domains that contain their own function spaces, i.e. one gets functions that can be applied to themselves.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Beside these desirable properties, domain theory also allows for an appealing intuitive interpretation.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] As mentioned above, the domains of computation are always partially ordered.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] This ordering represents a hierarchy of information or knowledge.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The higher an element is within the order, the more specific it is and the more information it contains.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Lower elements represent incomplete knowledge or intermediate results.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Computation then is modeled by applying monotone functions repeatedly on elements of the domain in order to refine a result.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Reaching a fixed point is equivalent to finishing a calculation.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Domains provide a superior setting for these ideas since fixed points of monotone functions can be guaranteed to exist and, under additional restrictions, can be approximated from below.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In this section, the central concepts and definitions of domain theory will be introduced.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The above intuition of domains being *information orderings* will be emphasized to motivate the mathematical formalization of the theory.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The precise formal definitions are to be found in the dedicated articles for each concept.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] A list of general order-theoretic definitions, which include domain theoretic notions as well can be found in the order theory glossary.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The most important concepts of domain theory will nonetheless be introduced below.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] As mentioned before, domain theory deals with partially ordered sets to model a domain of computation.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The goal is to interpret the elements of such an order as *pieces of information* or *(partial) results of a computation*, where elements that are higher in the order extend the information of the elements below them in a consistent way.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] From this simple intuition it is already clear that domains often do not have a greatest element, since this would mean that there is an element that contains the information of *all* other elements—a rather uninteresting situation.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] A concept that plays an important role in the theory is that of a **directed subset** of a domain; a directed subset is a non-empty subset of the order in which any two elements have an upper bound that is an element of this subset.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In view of our intuition about domains, this means that any two pieces of information within the directed subset are *consistently* extended by some other element in the subset.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Hence we can view directed subsets as *consistent specifications*, i.e. as sets of partial results in which no two elements are contradictory.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] This interpretation can be compared with the notion of a convergent sequence in analysis, where each element is more specific than the preceding one.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Indeed, in the theory of metric spaces, sequences play a role that is in many aspects analogous to the role of directed sets in domain theory.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Now, as in the case of sequences, we are interested in the *limit* of a directed set.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] According to what was said above, this would be an element that is the most general piece of information that extends the information of all elements of the directed set, i.e. the unique element that contains *exactly* the information that was present in the directed set, and nothing more.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In the formalization of order theory, this is just the **least upper bound** of the directed set.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] As in the case of the limit of a sequence, the least upper bound of a directed set does not always exist.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Naturally, one has a special interest in those domains of computations in which all consistent specifications *converge*, i.e. in orders in which all directed sets have a least upper bound.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] This property defines the class of **directed-complete partial orders**, or **dcpo** for short.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Indeed, most considerations of domain theory do only consider orders that are at least directed complete.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] From the underlying idea of partially specified results as representing incomplete knowledge, one derives another desirable property: the existence of a **least element**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Such an element models that state of no information—the place where most computations start.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] It also can be regarded as the output of a computation that does not return any result at all.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Now that we have some basic formal descriptions of what a domain of computation should be, we can turn to the computations themselves.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Clearly, these have to be functions, taking inputs from some computational domain and returning outputs in some (possibly different) domain.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] However, one would also expect that the output of a function will contain more information when the information content of the input is increased.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Formally, this means that we want a function to be **monotonic**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] When dealing with **dcpos**, one might also want computations to be compatible with the formation of limits of a directed set.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Formally, this means that, for some function *f*, the image *f*(*D*) of a directed set *D* (i.e. the set of the images of each element of *D*) is again directed and has as a least upper bound the image of the least upper bound of *D*.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] One could also say that *f* *preserves directed suprema*.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Also note that, by considering directed sets of two elements, such a function also has to be monotonic.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] These properties give rise to the notion of a **Scott-continuous** function.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Since this often is not ambiguous one also may speak of *continuous functions*.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Domain theory is a purely *qualitative* approach to modeling the structure of information states.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] One can say that something contains more information, but the amount of additional information is not specified.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Yet, there are some situations in which one wants to speak about elements that are in a sense much simpler (or much more incomplete) than a given state of information.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] For example, in the natural subset-inclusion ordering on some powerset, any infinite element (i.e. set) is much more "informative" than any of its *finite* subsets.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] If one wants to model such a relationship, one may first want to consider the induced strict order < of a domain with order ≤.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] However, while this is a useful notion in the case of total orders, it does not tell us much in the case of partially ordered sets.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Considering again inclusion-orders of sets, a set is already strictly smaller than another, possibly infinite, set if it contains just one less element.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] One would, however, hardly agree that this captures the notion of being "much simpler".
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] A more elaborate approach leads to the definition of the so-called **order of approximation**, which is more suggestively also called the **way-below relation**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] since the singleton set {*y*} is directed.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] For an example, in an ordering of sets, an infinite set is way above any of its finite subsets.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Since the supremum of this chain is the set of all natural numbers **N**, this shows that no infinite set is way below **N**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] However, being way below some element is a *relative* notion and does not reveal much about an element alone.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] For example, one would like to characterize finite sets in an order-theoretic way, but even infinite sets can be way below some other set.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The special property of these **finite** elements *x* is that they are way below themselves, i.e.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] An element with this property is also called **compact**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Yet, such elements do not have to be "finite" nor "compact" in any other mathematical usage of the terms.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The notation is nonetheless motivated by certain parallels to the respective notions in set theory and topology.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The compact elements of a domain have the important special property that they cannot be obtained as a limit of a directed set in which they did not already occur.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Many other important results about the way-below relation support the claim that this definition is appropriate to capture many important aspects of a domain.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The previous thoughts raise another question: is it possible to guarantee that all elements of a domain can be obtained as a limit of much simpler elements?
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] This is quite relevant in practice, since we cannot compute infinite objects but we may still hope to approximate them arbitrarily closely.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] More generally, we would like to restrict to a certain subset of elements as being sufficient for getting all other elements as least upper bounds.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Hence, one defines a **base** of a poset *P* as being a subset *B* of *P*, such that, for each *x* in *P*, the set of elements in *B* that are way below *x* contains a directed set with supremum *x*.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The poset *P* is a **continuous poset** if it has some base.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Especially, *P* itself is a base in this situation.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In many applications, one restricts to continuous (d)cpos as a main object of study.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Finally, an even stronger restriction on a partially ordered set is given by requiring the existence of a base of *finite* elements.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] From the viewpoint of denotational semantics, algebraic posets are particularly well-behaved, since they allow for the approximation of all elements even when restricting to finite ones.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] As remarked before, not every finite element is "finite" in a classical sense and it may well be that the finite elements constitute an uncountable set.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In some cases, however, the base for a poset is countable.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] In this case, one speaks of an **ω-continuous** poset.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Accordingly, if the countable base consists entirely of finite elements, we obtain an order that is **ω-algebraic**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] A simple special case of a domain is known as an **elementary** or **flat domain**.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] This consists of a set of incomparable elements, such as the integers, along with a single "bottom" element considered smaller than all other elements.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] One can obtain a number of other interesting special classes of ordered structures that could be suitable as "domains".
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] We already mentioned continuous posets and algebraic posets.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] More special versions of both are continuous and algebraic cpos.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Adding even further completeness properties one obtains continuous lattices and algebraic lattices, which are just complete lattices with the respective properties.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] For the algebraic case, one finds broader classes of posets that are still worth studying: historically, the Scott domains were the first structures to be studied in domain theory.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Still wider classes of domains are constituted by SFP-domains, L-domains, and bifinite domains.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] All of these classes of orders can be cast into various categories of dcpos, using functions that are monotone, Scott-continuous, or even more specialized as morphisms.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] Finally, note that the term *domain* itself is not exact and thus is only used as an abbreviation when a formal definition has been given before or when the details are irrelevant.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] (Markowsky's theorem) A poset *D* is a dcpo if and only if it is a chain complete poset, meaning that each chain in *D* has a supremum.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] The $\sqcup$ symbol is the directed join.
[src:denotational-domains/domain-theory] A continuity space is a generalization of metric spaces and posets that can be used to unify the notions of metric spaces and domains.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] In mathematical order theory, an **ideal** is a special subset of a partially ordered set (poset).
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Although this term historically was derived from the notion of a ring ideal of abstract algebra, it has subsequently been generalized to a different notion.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Ideals are of great importance for many constructions in order and lattice theory.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] 3. for every *x*, *y* in I, there is some element *z* in I, such that *x* ≤ *z* and *y* ≤ *z* (I is a directed set).
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] While this is the most general way to define an ideal for arbitrary posets, it was originally defined for lattices only.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] In this case, the following equivalent definition can be given: a subset I of a lattice $(P,\leq )$ is an ideal if and only if it is a lower set that is closed under finite joins (suprema); that is, it is nonempty and for all *x*, *y* in I, the element $x\vee y$ of *P* is also in I.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] A weaker notion of **order ideal** is defined to be a subset of a poset P that satisfies the above conditions 1 and 2.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] In other words, an order ideal is simply a lower set.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Similarly, an ideal can also be defined as a "directed lower set".
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] The dual notion of an ideal, i.e., the concept obtained by reversing all ≤ and exchanging $\vee$ with $\wedge ,$ is a filter.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Frink ideals, pseudoideals and Doyle pseudoideals are different generalizations of the notion of a lattice ideal.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] An ideal or filter is said to be **proper** if it is not equal to the whole set *P*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] The smallest ideal that contains a given element *p* is a *principal ideal* and *p* is said to be a *principal element* of the ideal in this situation.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] The principal ideal $\downarrow p$ for a principal *p* is thus given by ↓ *p* = {*x* ∈ *P* | *x* ≤ *p*}.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] The above definitions of "ideal" and "order ideal" are the standard ones, but there is some confusion in terminology.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Sometimes the words and definitions such as "ideal", "order ideal", "Frink ideal", or "partial order ideal" mean one another.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] An important special case of an ideal is constituted by those ideals whose set-theoretic complements are filters, i.e. ideals in the inverse order.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Such ideals are called **prime ideals**.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Also note that, since we require ideals and filters to be non-empty, every prime ideal is necessarily proper.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] 2. for all elements *x* and *y* of *P*, $x\wedge y$ in I implies that *x* ∈ *I* or *y* ∈ *I*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] It is easily checked that this is indeed equivalent to stating that $P\setminus I$ is a filter (which is then also prime, in the dual sense).
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] For a complete lattice the further notion of a **completely prime ideal** is meaningful.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] It is defined to be a proper ideal I with the additional property that, whenever the meet (infimum) of some arbitrary set *A* is in *I*, some element of *A* is also in I.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] So this is just a specific prime ideal that extends the above conditions to infinite meets.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] The existence of prime ideals is in general not obvious, and often a satisfactory amount of prime ideals cannot be derived within ZF (Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory without the axiom of choice).
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] This issue is discussed in various prime ideal theorems, which are necessary for many applications that require prime ideals.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] An ideal I is a *maximal ideal* if it is proper and there is no *proper* ideal *J* that is a strict superset of I.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Likewise, a filter *F* is maximal if it is proper and there is no proper filter that is a strict superset.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] When a poset is a distributive lattice, maximal ideals and filters are necessarily prime, while the converse of this statement is false in general.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Maximal filters are sometimes called ultrafilters, but this terminology is often reserved for Boolean algebras, where a maximal filter (ideal) is a filter (ideal) that contains exactly one of the elements {*a*, ¬*a*}, for each element *a* of the Boolean algebra.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] In Boolean algebras, the terms *prime ideal* and *maximal ideal* coincide, as do the terms *prime filter* and *maximal filter*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] There is another interesting notion of maximality of ideals: Consider an ideal I and a filter *F* such that I is disjoint from *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] We are interested in an ideal *M* that is maximal among all ideals that contain I and are disjoint from *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] In the case of distributive lattices such an *M* is always a prime ideal.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Assume the ideal *M* is maximal with respect to disjointness from the filter *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Suppose for a contradiction that *M* is not prime, i.e. there exists a pair of elements *a* and *b* such that *a* ∧ *b* in *M* but neither *a* nor *b* are in *M*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Consider the case that for all *m* in *M*, *m* ∨ *a* is not in *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] One can construct an ideal *N* by taking the downward closure of the set of all binary joins of this form, i.e.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] It is readily checked that *N* is indeed an ideal disjoint from *F* which is strictly greater than *M*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] But this contradicts the maximality of *M* and thus the assumption that *M* is not prime.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] For the other case, assume that there is some *m* in *M* with *m* ∨ *a* in *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Now if any element *n* in *M* is such that *n* ∨ *b* is in *F*, one finds that (*m* ∨ *n*) ∨ *b* and (*m* ∨ *n*) ∨ *a* are both in *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] But then their meet is in *F* and, by distributivity, (*m* ∨ *n*) ∨ (*a* ∧ *b*) is in *F* too.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] On the other hand, this finite join of elements of *M* is clearly in *M*, such that the assumed existence of *n* contradicts the disjointness of the two sets.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Hence all elements *n* of *M* have a join with *b* that is not in *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Consequently one can apply the above construction with *b* in place of *a* to obtain an ideal that is strictly greater than *M* while being disjoint from *F*.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] However, in general it is not clear whether there exists any ideal *M* that is maximal in this sense.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Yet, if we assume the axiom of choice in our set theory, then the existence of *M* for every disjoint filter–ideal-pair can be shown.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] In the special case that the considered order is a Boolean algebra, this theorem is called the Boolean prime ideal theorem.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] It is strictly weaker than the axiom of choice and it turns out that nothing more is needed for many order-theoretic applications of ideals.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] The construction of ideals and filters is an important tool in many applications of order theory.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Stone first for Boolean algebras, where the name was derived from the ring ideals of abstract algebra.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] He adopted this terminology because, using the isomorphism of the categories of Boolean algebras and of Boolean rings, the two notions do indeed coincide.
[src:denotational-domains/ideal-order-theory] Generalization to any posets was done by Frink.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] In denotational semantics and domain theory, **power domains** are domains of nondeterministic and concurrent computations.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] The idea of power domains for functions is that a nondeterministic function may be described as a deterministic set-valued function, where the set contains all values the nondeterministic function can take for a given argument.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] For concurrent systems, the idea is to express the set of all possible computations.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Roughly speaking, a power domain is a domain whose elements are certain subsets of a domain.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Taking this approach naively, though, often gives rise to domains that don't quite have the desired properties, and so one is led to increasingly complicated notions of the power domain.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] There are three common variants: the Plotkin, upper, and lower power domains.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] One way to understand these concepts is as free models of theories of nondeterminism.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] For most of this article we use the terms "domain" and "continuous function" quite loosely, meaning respectively some kind of ordered structure and some kind of limit-preserving function.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] This flexibility is genuine; for example, in some concurrent systems it is natural to impose the condition that every message sent must eventually be delivered.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] However, the limit of a chain of approximations in which a message was not delivered, would be a completed computation in which the message was never delivered!
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] A modern reference to this subject is the chapter by Abramsky and Jung [1994].
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Older references include those of Plotkin [1983, Chapter 8] and Smyth [1978].
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Domain theorists have come to understand power domains abstractly as free models for theories of non-determinism.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Just as the finite-powerset construction is the free semilattice, the powerdomain constructions should be understood abstractly as free models of theories of non-determinism.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] By changing the theories of non-determinism, different power domains arise.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] The abstract characterisation of powerdomains is often the easiest way to work with them, because explicit descriptions are so intricate.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] We recall three theories of non-determinism.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] They are variations of the theory of semilattices.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] The theories are not algebraic theories in the conventional sense, because some involve the order of the underlying domain.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] All theories have one sort *X*, and one binary operation ∪.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] The idea is that the operation ∪: *X* × *X* → *X* takes two combinations and returns the non-deterministic choice of them.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] A model of the Plotkin powertheory is a continuous semilattice: it is a semilattice whose carrier is a domain and for which the operation is continuous.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Note that the operator need not be a meet or join for the order of the domain.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] A morphism of continuous semilattices is a continuous function between their carriers that is also a semilattice homomorphism.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Models of the lower powertheory are called inflationary semilattices; there is an additional requirement that the operator behave somewhat like a join for the order.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] For the upper powertheory, models are called deflationary semilattices; here, the operator behaves somewhat like a meet.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] The Plotkin powerdomain on *D* is the free model of the Plotkin powertheory over *D*.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Other powerdomains are defined abstractly in a similar manner.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] In other words, *P*[*D*] is the collection of downward-closed subsets of *D* that are also closed under existing least upper bounds of directed sets in *D*.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Note that while the ordering on *P*[*D*] is given by the subset relation, least upper bounds do not in general coincide with unions.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] It is important to check which properties of domains are preserved by the power domain constructions.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] For example, the Hoare powerdomain of an ω-complete domain is again ω-complete.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Clinger [1981] constructed a power domain for the actor model building on the base domain of Actor event diagrams, which is incomplete.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Hewitt [2006] constructed a power domain for the actor model (which is technically simpler and easier to understand than Clinger's model) building on a base domain of timed Actor event diagrams, which is complete.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] The idea is to attach an arrival time for each message received by an Actor.
[src:denotational-domains/powerdomain] Domains can be understood as topological spaces, and, in this setting, the power domain constructions can be connected with the *space of subsets* construction introduced by Leopold Vietoris.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] In mathematics, given two partially ordered sets *P* and *Q*, a function *f* : *P* → *Q* between them is **Scott-continuous** (named after the mathematician Dana Scott) if it preserves all directed suprema.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] That is, for every directed subset *D* of *P* with supremum in *P*, its image has a supremum in *Q*, and that supremum is the image of the supremum of *D*, i.e. $\sqcup f[D]=f(\sqcup D)$ , where $\sqcup$ is the directed join.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] When Q is the poset of truth values, i.e.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] Sierpiński space, then Scott-continuous functions are characteristic functions of open sets, and thus Sierpiński space is the classifying space for open sets.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] A subset *O* of a partially ordered set *P* is called **Scott-open** if it is an upper set and if it is **inaccessible by directed joins**, i.e. if all directed sets *D* with supremum in *O* have non-empty intersection with *O*.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] The Scott-open subsets of a partially ordered set *P* form a topology on *P*, the **Scott topology**.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] A function between partially ordered sets is Scott-continuous if and only if it is continuous with respect to the Scott topology.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] The Scott topology was first defined by Dana Scott for complete lattices and later defined for arbitrary partially ordered sets.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] Scott-continuous functions are used in the study of models for lambda calculi and the denotational semantics of computer programs.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] A Scott-continuous function is always monotonic, meaning that if $A\leq _{P}B$ for $A,B\in P$ , then $f(A)\leq _{Q}f(B)$ .
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] A subset of a directed complete partial order is closed with respect to the Scott topology induced by the partial order if and only if it is a lower set and closed under suprema of directed subsets.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] A directed complete partial order (dcpo) with the Scott topology is always a Kolmogorov space (i.e., it satisfies the T0 separation axiom).
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] However, a dcpo with the Scott topology is a Hausdorff space if and only if the order is trivial.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] The Scott-open sets form a complete lattice when ordered by inclusion.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] For any Kolmogorov space, the topology induces an order relation on that space, the specialization order: *x* ≤ *y* if and only if every open neighbourhood of *x* is also an open neighbourhood of *y*.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] The order relation of a dcpo *D* can be reconstructed from the Scott-open sets as the specialization order induced by the Scott topology.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] However, a dcpo equipped with the Scott topology need not be sober: the specialization order induced by the topology of a sober space makes that space into a dcpo, but the Scott topology derived from this order is finer than the original topology.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] The open sets in a given topological space when ordered by inclusion form a lattice on which the Scott topology can be defined.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] A subset *X* of a topological space *T* is compact with respect to the topology on *T* (in the sense that every open cover of *X* contains a finite subcover of *X*) if and only if the set of open neighbourhoods of *X* is open with respect to the Scott topology.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] For **CPO**, the cartesian closed category of dcpo's, two particularly notable examples of Scott-continuous functions are curry and apply.
[src:denotational-domains/scott-continuity] Nuel Belnap used Scott continuity to extend logical connectives to a four-valued logic.
